# Release changelog requirements

Before running `scripts/release.sh` or `scripts/release.ps1`, every user-facing change since the last release must be documented.

## When to write changelog entries

Add entries under `## [Unreleased]` in `CHANGELOG.md` as features, fixes, or refactors land — not only at release time.

Use these sections when they apply:

- `Added` — new features or UI
- `Changed` — behavior or UX updates
- `Fixed` — bug fixes
- `Removed` — deprecated or removed behavior

Write short, user-facing bullets. Link issues or PRs only when helpful.

## Before releasing

1. Review `git log` and the working tree since the last tag.
2. Move all `[Unreleased]` bullets into a new version section:

   ```markdown
   ## [1.0.6] - 2026-06-11

   ### Added
   - ...
   ```

3. Leave an empty `## [Unreleased]` section at the top.
4. Commit `CHANGELOG.md` with the version bump (release scripts validate the version section exists).
5. Run the release script only after the changelog is complete.

## GitHub Releases

Release notes on GitHub must match the new `CHANGELOG.md` section for that version. CI reads that section via `scripts/extract-changelog-notes.mjs` — do not rely on auto-generated notes alone.

If a release already exists and notes need correction, edit them on GitHub to match `CHANGELOG.md`.

## Agent checklist

When implementing new features or fixes:

- [ ] Add or update bullets under `[Unreleased]` in `CHANGELOG.md`
- [ ] Update `docs/RELEASING.md` or feature docs only when release process or architecture changes

When preparing a release:

- [ ] Finalize the `## [x.y.z]` section in `CHANGELOG.md`
- [ ] Confirm release scripts pass changelog validation
- [ ] Verify the GitHub Release body matches the changelog after CI finishes
